# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-bigquery
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data analysis challenges include capturing data, data storage, data analysis, search, sharing, transfer, visualization, querying, updating, information privacy, and data sources.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data was originally associated with three key concepts: *volume*, *variety*, and *velocity*.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The analysis of big data that have only volume, velocity, and variety can pose challenges in sampling.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] A fourth concept, *veracity,* which refers to the level of reliability of data, was thus added.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Current usage of the term *big data* tends to refer to the use of predictive analytics, user behavior analytics, or certain other advanced data analytics methods that extract value from big data, and seldom to a particular size of data set.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] "There is little doubt that the quantities of data now available are indeed large, but that's not the most relevant characteristic of this new data ecosystem." Analysis of data sets can find new correlations to "spot business trends, prevent diseases, combat crime and so on".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Scientists, business executives, medical practitioners, advertising and governments alike regularly meet difficulties with large datasets in areas including Internet searches, fintech, healthcare analytics, geographic information systems, urban informatics, and business informatics.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Scientists encounter limitations in e-Science work, including meteorology, genomics, connectomics, complex physics simulations, biology, and environmental research.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The world's technological per-capita capacity to store information has roughly doubled every 40 months since the 1980s; as of 2012, every day 2.5 exabytes (2.17×260 bytes) of data are generated.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Based on an IDC report prediction, the global data volume was predicted to grow exponentially from 4.4 zettabytes to 44 zettabytes between 2013 and 2020.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] By 2025, IDC predicts there will be 163 zettabytes of data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] According to IDC, global spending on big data and business analytics (BDA) solutions is estimated to reach $215.7 billion in 2021.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Statista reported that the global big data market is forecasted to grow to $103 billion by 2027.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In 2011 McKinsey & Company reported, if US healthcare were to use big data creatively and effectively to drive efficiency and quality, the sector could create more than $300 billion in value every year.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In the developed economies of Europe, government administrators could save more than €100 billion ($149 billion) in operational efficiency improvements alone by using big data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] And users of services enabled by personal-location data could capture $600 billion in consumer surplus.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] One question for large enterprises is determining who should own big-data initiatives that affect the entire organization.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Relational database management systems and desktop statistical software packages used to visualize data often have difficulty processing and analyzing big data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The processing and analysis of big data may require "massively parallel software running on tens, hundreds, or even thousands of servers".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] What qualifies as "big data" varies depending on the capabilities of those analyzing it and their tools.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Furthermore, expanding capabilities make big data a moving target.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] "For some organizations, facing hundreds of gigabytes of data for the first time may trigger a need to reconsider data management options.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The term *big data* has been in use since the 1990s, with some giving credit to John Mashey for popularizing the term.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data usually includes data sets with sizes beyond the ability of commonly used software tools to capture, curate, manage, and process data within a tolerable elapsed time.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data philosophy encompasses unstructured, semi-structured and structured data; however, the main focus is on unstructured data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data "size" is a constantly moving target; as of 2012 ranging from a few dozen terabytes to many zettabytes of data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data requires a set of techniques and technologies with new forms of integration to reveal insights from datasets that are diverse, complex, and of a massive scale.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Variability is often included as an additional quality of big data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In a comparative study of big datasets, Kitchin and McArdle found that none of the commonly considered characteristics of big data appear consistently across all of the analyzed cases.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] For this reason, other studies identified the redefinition of power dynamics in knowledge discovery as the defining trait.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Instead of focusing on the intrinsic characteristics of big data, this alternative perspective pushes forward a relational understanding of the object claiming that what matters is the way in which data is collected, stored, made available and analyzed.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The quantity of generated and stored data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The size of the data determines the value and potential insight, and whether it can be considered big data or not.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The size of big data is usually larger than terabytes and petabytes.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Earlier technologies like RDBMSs were capable to handle structured data efficiently and effectively.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] However, the change in type and nature from structured to semi-structured or unstructured challenged the existing tools and technologies.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data technologies evolved with the prime intention to capture, store, and process the semi-structured and unstructured (variety) data generated with high speed (velocity), and huge in size (volume).
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Later, these tools and technologies were explored and used for handling structured data also but preferable for storage.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Eventually, the processing of structured data was still kept as optional, either using big data or traditional RDBMSs.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] This helps in analyzing data towards effective usage of the hidden insights exposed from the data collected via social media, log files, sensors, etc.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The speed at which the data is generated and processed to meet the demands and challenges that lie in the path of growth and development.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data is often available in real-time.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] , big data is produced more continually.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Two kinds of velocity related to big data are the frequency of generation and the frequency of handling, recording, and publishing.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The truthfulness or reliability of the data, which refers to the data quality and the data value.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data must not only be large in size, but also must be reliable in order to achieve value in the analysis of it.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] of captured data can vary greatly, affecting an accurate analysis.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The worth in information that can be achieved by the processing and analysis of large datasets.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Value also can be measured by an assessment of the other qualities of big data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Value may also represent the profitability of information that is retrieved from the analysis of big data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Unlike variety, variability captures the notion the fact that formats, structure, or sources of big data change through time and given different circumstances.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Interpretation of data depends on a changing context, and with a different context, the old meanings may become invalid.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data may or may not include all the available data from sources.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Respectively, the proportion of specific data of each element per element collected and if the element and its characteristics are properly indexed or identified.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] If the data collected contains common fields that would enable a conjoining, or meta-analysis, of different data sets.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] If new fields in each element of the data collected can be added or changed easily.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] If the size of the big data storage system can expand rapidly.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data repositories have existed in many forms, often built by corporations with a special need.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Commercial vendors historically offered parallel database management systems for big data beginning in the 1990s.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] For many years, WinterCorp published the largest database report.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Teradata Corporation in 1984 marketed the parallel processing DBC 1012 system.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Teradata systems were the first to store and analyze 1 terabyte of data in 1992.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Hard disk drives were 2.5 GB in 1991 so the definition of big data continuously evolves.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Teradata installed the first petabyte class RDBMS based system in 2007.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] As of 2017, there are a few dozen petabyte class Teradata relational databases installed, the largest of which exceeds 50 PB.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Systems up until 2008 were 100% structured relational data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Since then, Teradata has added semi structured data types including XML, JSON, and Avro.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] (now LexisNexis Risk Solutions) developed a C++-based distributed platform for data processing and querying known as the HPCC Systems platform.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] This system automatically partitions, distributes, stores and delivers structured, semi-structured, and unstructured data across multiple commodity servers.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Users can write data processing pipelines and queries in a declarative dataflow programming language called ECL.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Data analysts working in ECL are not required to define data schemas upfront and can rather focus on the particular problem at hand, reshaping data in the best possible manner as they develop the solution.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In 2004, LexisNexis acquired Seisint Inc. and their high-speed parallel processing platform and successfully used this platform to integrate the data systems of Choicepoint Inc. when they acquired that company in 2008.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In 2011, the HPCC systems platform was open-sourced under the Apache v2.0 License.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] CERN and other physics experiments have collected big data sets for many decades, usually analyzed via high-throughput computing rather than the map-reduce architectures usually meant by the current "big data" movement.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In 2004, Google published a paper on a process called MapReduce that uses a similar architecture.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The MapReduce concept provides a parallel processing model, and an associated implementation was released to process huge amounts of data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] With MapReduce, queries are split and distributed across parallel nodes and processed in parallel (the "map" step).
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The results are then gathered and delivered (the "reduce" step).
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The framework was very successful, so others wanted to replicate the algorithm.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Therefore, an implementation of the MapReduce framework was adopted by an Apache open-source project named "Hadoop".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Apache Spark was developed in 2012 in response to limitations in the MapReduce paradigm, as it adds in-memory processing and the ability to set up many operations (not just map followed by reducing).
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] MIKE2.0 is an open approach to information management that acknowledges the need for revisions due to big data implications identified in an article titled "Big Data Solution Offering".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The methodology addresses handling big data in terms of useful permutations of data sources, complexity in interrelationships, and difficulty in deleting (or modifying) individual records.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Studies in 2012 showed that a multiple-layer architecture was one option to address the issues that big data presents.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] A distributed parallel architecture distributes data across multiple servers; these parallel execution environments can dramatically improve data processing speeds.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] This type of architecture inserts data into a parallel DBMS, which implements the use of MapReduce and Hadoop frameworks.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] This type of framework looks to make the processing power transparent to the end-user by using a front-end application server.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The data lake allows an organization to shift its focus from centralized control to a shared model to respond to the changing dynamics of information management.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] This enables quick segregation of data into the data lake, thereby reducing the overhead time.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Multidimensional big data can also be represented as OLAP data cubes or, mathematically, tensors.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Array database systems have set out to provide storage and high-level query support on this data type.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Although, many approaches and technologies have been developed, it still remains difficult to carry out machine learning with big data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Some MPP relational databases have the ability to store and manage petabytes of data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Implicit is the ability to load, monitor, back up, and optimize the use of the large data tables in the RDBMS.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] DARPA's Topological Data Analysis program seeks the fundamental structure of massive data sets and in 2008 the technology went public with the launch of a company called "Ayasdi".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The practitioners of big data analytics processes are generally hostile to slower shared storage, preferring direct-attached storage (DAS) in its various forms from solid state drive (SSD) to high capacity SATA disk buried inside parallel processing nodes.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The perception of shared storage architectures—storage area network (SAN) and network-attached storage (NAS)— is that they are relatively slow, complex, and expensive.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] These qualities are not consistent with big data analytics systems that thrive on system performance, commodity infrastructure, and low cost.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Real or near-real-time information delivery is one of the defining characteristics of big data analytics.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Latency is therefore avoided whenever and wherever possible.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Data in direct-attached memory or disk is good—data on memory or disk at the other end of an FC SAN connection is not.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The cost of an SAN at the scale needed for analytics applications is much higher than other storage techniques.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data has increased the demand of information management specialists so much so that Software AG, Oracle Corporation, IBM, Microsoft, SAP, EMC, HP, and Dell have spent more than $15 billion on software firms specializing in data management and analytics.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In 2010, this industry was worth more than $100 billion and was growing at almost 10 percent a year, about twice as fast as the software business as a whole.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Developed economies increasingly use data-intensive technologies.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] There are 4.6 billion mobile-phone subscriptions worldwide, and between 1 billion and 2 billion people accessing the internet.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Between 1990 and 2005, more than 1 billion people worldwide entered the middle class, which means more people became more literate, which in turn led to information growth.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The world's effective capacity to exchange information through telecommunication networks was 281 petabytes in 1986, 471 petabytes in 1993, 2.2 exabytes in 2000, 65 exabytes in 2007 and predictions put the amount of internet traffic at 667 exabytes annually by 2014.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] According to one estimate, one-third of the globally stored information is in the form of alphanumeric text and still image data, which is the format most useful for most big data applications.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] This also shows the potential of yet unused data (i.e. in the form of video and audio content).
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] While many vendors offer off-the-shelf products for big data, experts promote the development of in-house custom-tailored systems if the company has sufficient technical capabilities.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The use and adoption of big data within governmental processes allows efficiencies in terms of cost, productivity, and innovation, but comes with flaws.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Data analysis often requires multiple parts of government (central and local) to work in collaboration and create new and innovative processes to deliver the desired outcome.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] A common government organization that makes use of big data is the National Security Agency (NSA), which monitors the activities of the Internet constantly in search for potential patterns of suspicious or illegal activities their system may pick up.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Civil registration and vital statistics (CRVS) collects all certificates status from birth to death.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] CRVS is a source of big data for governments.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Research on the effective usage of information and communication technologies for development (also known as "ICT4D") suggests that big data technology can make important contributions but also present unique challenges to international development.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Advancements in big data analysis offer cost-effective opportunities to improve decision-making in critical development areas such as health care, employment, economic productivity, crime, security, and natural disaster and resource management.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Additionally, user-generated data offers new opportunities to give the unheard a voice.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] However, longstanding challenges for developing regions such as inadequate technological infrastructure and economic and human resource scarcity exacerbate existing concerns with big data such as privacy, imperfect methodology, and interoperability issues.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The challenge of "big data for development" is currently evolving toward the application of this data through machine learning, known as "artificial intelligence for development (AI4D).
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] A major practical application of big data for development has been "fighting poverty with data".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In 2015, Blumenstock and colleagues estimated predicted poverty and wealth from mobile phone metadata and in 2016 Jean and colleagues combined satellite imagery and machine learning to predict poverty.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] At the same time, working with digital trace data instead of traditional survey data does not eliminate the traditional challenges involved in the field of international quantitative analysis.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Priorities may change, but the fundamental discussions remain the same.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big Data is being rapidly adopted in Finance to 1) speed up processing and 2) deliver better, more informed inferences, both internally and to the clients of the financial institutions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big Data has also been a typical concept within the field of alternative financial service.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Some of the major areas involve crowd-funding platforms and crypto currency exchanges.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Some areas of improvement are more aspirational than actually implemented.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The level of data generated within healthcare systems is not trivial.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] With the added adoption of mHealth, eHealth and wearable technologies the volume of data will continue to increase.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] This includes electronic health record data, imaging data, patient generated data, sensor data, and other forms of difficult to process data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] There is now an even greater need for such environments to pay greater attention to data and information quality.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] While extensive information in healthcare is now electronic, it fits under the big data umbrella as most is unstructured and difficult to use.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The use of big data in healthcare has raised significant ethical challenges ranging from risks for individual rights, privacy and autonomy, to transparency and trust.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data in health research is particularly promising in terms of exploratory biomedical research, as data-driven analysis can move forward more quickly than hypothesis-driven research.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Then, trends seen in data analysis can be tested in traditional, hypothesis-driven follow up biological research and eventually clinical research.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] A related application sub-area, that heavily relies on big data, within the healthcare field is that of computer-aided diagnosis in medicine.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] For instance, for epilepsy monitoring it is customary to create 5 to 10 GB of data daily.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Similarly, a single uncompressed image of breast tomosynthesis averages 450 MB of data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] These are just a few of the many examples where computer-aided diagnosis uses big data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] For this reason, big data has been recognized as one of the seven key challenges that computer-aided diagnosis systems need to overcome in order to reach the next level of performance.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] A McKinsey Global Institute study found a shortage of 1.5 million highly trained data professionals and managers and a number of universities including University of Tennessee and UC Berkeley, have created masters programs to meet this demand.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Private boot camps have also developed programs to meet that demand, including paid programs like The Data Incubator or General Assembly.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In the specific field of marketing, one of the problems stressed by Wedel and Kannan is that marketing has several sub domains (e.g., advertising, promotions, product development, branding) that all use different types of data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] To understand how the media uses big data, it is first necessary to provide some context into the mechanism used for media process.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] It has been suggested by Nick Couldry and Joseph Turow that practitioners in media and advertising approach big data as many actionable points of information about millions of individuals.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The industry appears to be moving away from the traditional approach of using specific media environments such as newspapers, magazines, or television shows and instead taps into consumers with technologies that reach targeted people at optimal times in optimal locations.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The ultimate aim is to serve or convey, a message or content that is (statistically speaking) in line with the consumer's mindset.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] For example, publishing environments are increasingly tailoring messages (advertisements) and content (articles) to appeal to consumers that have been exclusively gleaned through various data-mining activities.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Channel 4, the British public-service television broadcaster, is a leader in the field of big data and data analysis.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Health insurance providers are collecting data on social "determinants of health" such as food and TV consumption, marital status, clothing size, and purchasing habits, from which they make predictions on health costs, in order to spot health issues in their clients.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] It is controversial whether these predictions are currently being used for pricing.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data and the IoT work in conjunction.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Data extracted from IoT devices provides a mapping of device inter-connectivity.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Such mappings have been used by the media industry, companies, and governments to more accurately target their audience and increase media efficiency.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The IoT is also increasingly adopted as a means of gathering sensory data, and this sensory data has been used in medical, manufacturing and transportation contexts.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Especially since 2015, big data has come to prominence within business operations as a tool to help employees work more efficiently and streamline the collection and distribution of information technology (IT).
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The use of big data to resolve IT and data collection issues within an enterprise is called IT operations analytics (ITOA).
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] By applying big data principles into the concepts of machine intelligence and deep computing, IT departments can predict potential issues and prevent them.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] ITOA businesses offer platforms for systems management that bring data silos together and generate insights from the whole of the system rather than from isolated pockets of data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Compared to survey-based data collection, big data has low cost per data point, applies analysis techniques via machine learning and data mining, and includes diverse and new data sources, e.g., registers, social media, apps, and other forms digital data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Since 2018, survey scientists have started to examine how big data and survey science can complement each other to allow researchers and practitioners to improve the production of statistics and its quality.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In 2021, the founding members of BigSurv received the Warren J.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Mitofsky Innovators Award from the American Association for Public Opinion Research.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data is notable in marketing due to the constant "datafication" of everyday consumers of the internet, in which all forms of data are tracked.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The datafication of consumers can be defined as quantifying many of or all human behaviors for the purpose of marketing.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The increasingly digital world of rapid datafication makes this idea relevant to marketing because the amount of data constantly grows exponentially.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] It is predicted to increase from 44 to 163 zettabytes within the span of five years.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The size of big data can often be difficult to navigate for marketers.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] As a result, adopters of big data may find themselves at a disadvantage.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Algorithmic findings can be difficult to achieve with such large datasets.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data in marketing is a highly lucrative tool that can be used for large corporations, its value being as a result of the possibility of predicting significant trends, interests, or statistical outcomes in a consumer-based manner.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Real-time market responsiveness is important for marketers because of the ability to shift marketing efforts and correct to current trends, which is helpful in maintaining relevance to consumers.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] This can supply corporations with the information necessary to predict the wants and needs of consumers in advance.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Data-driven market ambidexterity are being highly fueled by big data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] New models and algorithms are being developed to make significant predictions about certain economic and social situations.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data can be used to improve training and understanding competitors, using sport sensors.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] It is also possible to predict winners in a match using big data analytics.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Future performance of players could be predicted as well.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Thus, players' value and salary is determined by data collected throughout the season.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In Formula One races, race cars with hundreds of sensors generate terabytes of data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] These sensors collect data points from tire pressure to fuel burn efficiency.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Based on the data, engineers and data analysts decide whether adjustments should be made in order to win a race.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Besides, using big data, race teams try to predict the time they will finish the race beforehand, based on simulations using data collected over the season.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic, big data was raised as a way to minimise the impact of the disease.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Significant applications of big data included minimizing the spread of the virus, case identification and development of medical treatment.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Governments used big data to track infected people to minimise spread.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Early adopters included China, Taiwan, South Korea, and Israel.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Encrypted search and cluster formation in big data were demonstrated in March 2014 at the American Society of Engineering Education.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Gautam Siwach engaged at *Tackling the challenges of Big Data* by MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory and Amir Esmailpour at the UNH Research Group investigated the key features of big data as the formation of clusters and their interconnections.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] They focused on the security of big data and the orientation of the term towards the presence of different types of data in an encrypted form at cloud interface by providing the raw definitions and real-time examples within the technology.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Moreover, they proposed an approach for identifying the encoding technique to advance towards an expedited search over encrypted text leading to the security enhancements in big data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In March 2012, The White House announced a national "Big Data Initiative" that consisted of six federal departments and agencies committing more than $200 million to big data research projects.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The initiative included a National Science Foundation "Expeditions in Computing" grant of $10 million over five years to the AMPLab at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The AMPLab also received funds from DARPA, and over a dozen industrial sponsors and uses big data to attack a wide range of problems from predicting traffic congestion to fighting cancer.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The White House Big Data Initiative also included a commitment by the Department of Energy to provide $25 million in funding over five years to establish the Scalable Data Management, Analysis and Visualization (SDAV) Institute, led by the Energy Department's Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The SDAV Institute aims to bring together the expertise of six national laboratories and seven universities to develop new tools to help scientists manage and visualize data on the department's supercomputers.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The U.S. state of Massachusetts announced the Massachusetts Big Data Initiative in May 2012, which provides funding from the state government and private companies to a variety of research institutions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology hosts the Intel Science and Technology Center for Big Data in the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, combining government, corporate, and institutional funding and research efforts.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The European Commission is funding the two-year-long Big Data Public Private Forum through their Seventh Framework Program to engage companies, academics and other stakeholders in discussing big data issues.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The project aims to define a strategy in terms of research and innovation to guide supporting actions from the European Commission in the successful implementation of the big data economy.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Outcomes of this project will be used as input for Horizon 2020, their next framework program.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The British government announced in March 2014 the founding of the Alan Turing Institute, named after the computer pioneer and code-breaker, which will focus on new ways to collect and analyze large data sets.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] At the University of Waterloo Stratford Campus Canadian Open Data Experience (CODE) Inspiration Day, participants demonstrated how using data visualization can increase the understanding and appeal of big data sets and communicate their story to the world.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Computational social sciences – Anyone can use application programming interfaces (APIs) provided by big data holders, such as Google and Twitter, to do research in the social and behavioral sciences.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Tobias Preis et al. used Google Trends data to demonstrate that Internet users from countries with a higher per capita gross domestic products (GDPs) are more likely to search for information about the future than information about the past.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The findings suggest there may be a link between online behaviors and real-world economic indicators.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The authors of the study examined Google queries logs made by ratio of the volume of searches for the coming year (2011) to the volume of searches for the previous year (2009), which they call the "future orientation index".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] They compared the future orientation index to the per capita GDP of each country, and found a strong tendency for countries where Google users inquire more about the future to have a higher GDP.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Tobias Preis and his colleagues Helen Susannah Moat and H.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Eugene Stanley introduced a method to identify online precursors for stock market moves, using trading strategies based on search volume data provided by Google Trends.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Their analysis of Google search volume for 98 terms of varying financial relevance, published in *Scientific Reports*, suggests that increases in search volume for financially relevant search terms tend to precede large losses in financial markets.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data sets come with algorithmic challenges that previously did not exist.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Hence, there is seen by some to be a need to fundamentally change the processing ways.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] A research question that is asked about big data sets is whether it is necessary to look at the full data to draw certain conclusions about the properties of the data or if is a sample is good enough.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] The name big data itself contains a term related to size and this is an important characteristic of big data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] But sampling enables the selection of right data points from within the larger data set to estimate the characteristics of the whole population.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] In manufacturing different types of sensory data such as acoustics, vibration, pressure, current, voltage, and controller data are available at short time intervals.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] To predict downtime it may not be necessary to look at all the data but a sample may be sufficient.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] Big data can be broken down by various data point categories such as demographic, psychographic, behavioral, and transactional data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p01] With large sets of data points, marketers are able to create and use more customized segments of consumers for more strategic targeting.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Critiques of the big data paradigm come in two flavors: those that question the implications of the approach itself, and those that question the way it is currently done.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] One approach to this criticism is the field of critical data studies.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Mark Graham has leveled broad critiques at Chris Anderson's assertion that big data will spell the end of theory: focusing in particular on the notion that big data must always be contextualized in their social, economic, and political contexts.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Even as companies invest eight- and nine-figure sums to derive insight from information streaming in from suppliers and customers, less than 40% of employees have sufficiently mature processes and skills to do so.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] To overcome this insight deficit, big data, no matter how comprehensive or well analyzed, must be complemented by "big judgment", according to an article in the *Harvard Business Review*.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Much in the same line, it has been pointed out that the decisions based on the analysis of big data are inevitably "informed by the world as it was in the past, or, at best, as it currently is".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Fed by a large number of data on past experiences, algorithms can predict future development if the future is similar to the past.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] If the system's dynamics of the future change (if it is not a stationary process), the past can say little about the future.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] In order to make predictions in changing environments, it would be necessary to have a thorough understanding of the systems dynamic, which requires theory.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] As a response to this critique Alemany Oliver and Vayre suggest to use "abductive reasoning as a first step in the research process in order to bring context to consumers' digital traces and make new theories emerge".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Additionally, it has been suggested to combine big data approaches with computer simulations, such as agent-based models and complex systems.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Agent-based models are increasingly getting better in predicting the outcome of social complexities of even unknown future scenarios through computer simulations that are based on a collection of mutually interdependent algorithms.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Finally, the use of multivariate methods that probe for the latent structure of the data, such as factor analysis and cluster analysis, have proven useful as analytic approaches that go well beyond the bi-variate approaches (e.g. contingency tables) typically employed with smaller data sets.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] In health and biology, conventional scientific approaches are based on experimentation.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] For these approaches, the limiting factor is the relevant data that can confirm or refute the initial hypothesis.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] A new postulate is accepted now in biosciences: the information provided by the data in huge volumes (omics) without prior hypothesis is complementary and sometimes necessary to conventional approaches based on experimentation.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] In the massive approaches it is the formulation of a relevant hypothesis to explain the data that is the limiting factor.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] The search logic is reversed and the limits of induction ("Glory of Science and Philosophy scandal", C.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Privacy advocates are concerned about the threat to privacy represented by increasing storage and integration of personally identifiable information; expert panels have released various policy recommendations to conform practice to expectations of privacy.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] The misuse of big data in several cases by media, companies, and even the government has allowed for abolition of trust in almost every fundamental institution holding up society.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Barocas and Nissenbaum argue that one way of protecting individual users is by being informed about the types of information being collected, with whom it is shared, under what constraints and for what purposes.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] The "V" model of big data is concerning as it centers around computational scalability and lacks in a loss around the perceptibility and understandability of information.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Large data sets have been analyzed by computing machines for well over a century, including the US census analytics performed by IBM's punch-card machines which computed statistics including means and variances of populations across the whole continent.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] In more recent decades, science experiments such as CERN have produced data on similar scales to current commercial "big data".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Ulf-Dietrich Reips and Uwe Matzat wrote in 2014 that big data had become a "fad" in scientific research.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Researcher danah boyd has raised concerns about the use of big data in science neglecting principles such as choosing a representative sample by being too concerned about handling the huge amounts of data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] This approach may lead to results that have a bias in one way or another.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Integration across heterogeneous data resources—some that might be considered big data and others not—presents formidable logistical as well as analytical challenges, but many researchers argue that such integrations are likely to represent the most promising new frontiers in science.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] In the provocative article "Critical Questions for Big Data", the authors title big data a part of mythology: "large data sets offer a higher form of intelligence and knowledge [...], with the aura of truth, objectivity, and accuracy".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Users of big data are often "lost in the sheer volume of numbers", and "working with Big Data is still subjective, and what it quantifies does not necessarily have a closer claim on objective truth".
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Recent developments in BI domain, such as pro-active reporting especially target improvements in the usability of big data, through automated filtering of non-useful data and correlations.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Big data analysis is often shallow compared to analysis of smaller data sets.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] In many big data projects, there is no large data analysis happening, but the challenge is the extract, transform, load part of data pre-processing.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Big data is a buzzword and a "vague term", but at the same time an "obsession" with entrepreneurs, consultants, scientists, and the media.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Big data showcases such as Google Flu Trends failed to deliver good predictions in recent years, overstating the flu outbreaks by a factor of two.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Similarly, Academy Awards and election predictions solely based on Twitter were more often off than on target.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Big data often poses the same challenges as small data; adding more data does not solve problems of bias, but may emphasize other problems.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] In particular data sources such as Twitter are not representative of the overall population, and results drawn from such sources may then lead to wrong conclusions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Google Translate—which is based on big data statistical analysis of text—does a good job at translating web pages.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] However, results from specialized domains may be dramatically skewed.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] On the other hand, big data may also introduce new problems, such as the multiple comparisons problem: simultaneously testing a large set of hypotheses is likely to produce many false results that mistakenly appear significant.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Furthermore, big data analytics results are only as good as the model on which they are predicated.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] In an example, big data took part in attempting to predict the results of the 2016 U.S. presidential election with varying degrees of success.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Big data has been used in policing and surveillance by institutions like law enforcement and corporations ().
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Due to the less visible nature of data-based surveillance as compared to traditional methods of policing, objections to big data policing are less likely to arise.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] If these potential problems are not corrected or regulated, the effects of big data policing may continue to shape societal hierarchies.
[src:gcp-bigquery/big-data-p02] Brayne also notes that the conscientious use of big data policing could prevent individual-level biases from becoming institutional biases.
[src:gcp-bigquery/bigquery] BigQuery originated from Google's internal Dremel technology, which enabled quick queries across trillions of rows of data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/bigquery] The product was originally announced in May 2010 at Google I/O.
[src:gcp-bigquery/bigquery] Initially, it was only usable by a limited number of external early adopters due to limitations on the API.
[src:gcp-bigquery/bigquery] However, after the product proved its potential, it was released for limited availability in 2011 and general availability in 2012.
[src:gcp-bigquery/bigquery] After general availability, BigQuery found success among a broad range of customers, including airlines, insurance, and retail organizations.
[src:gcp-bigquery/bigquery] BigQuery requires all requests to be authenticated, supporting a number of Google-proprietary mechanisms as well as OAuth.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:gcp-bigquery/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:gcp-bigquery/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In computing, **online analytical processing (OLAP)** (/ˈoʊlæp/), is an approach to quickly answer multi-dimensional analytical (MDA) queries.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The term *OLAP* was created as a slight modification of the traditional database term online transaction processing (OLTP).
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is part of the broader category of business intelligence, which also encompasses relational databases, report writing and data mining.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Typical applications of OLAP include business reporting for sales, marketing, management reporting, business process management (BPM), budgeting and forecasting, financial reporting and similar areas, with new applications emerging, such as agriculture.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP tools enable users to analyse multidimensional data interactively from multiple perspectives.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP consists of three basic analytical operations: consolidation (roll-up), drill-down, and slicing and dicing.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Consolidation involves the aggregation of data that can be accumulated and computed in one or more dimensions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] For example, all sales offices are rolled up to the sales department or sales division to anticipate sales trends.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] By contrast, the drill-down is a technique that allows users to navigate through the details.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] For instance, users can view the sales by individual products that make up a region's sales.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Slicing and dicing is a feature whereby users can take out (slicing) a specific set of data of the OLAP cube and view (dicing) the slices from different viewpoints.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] These viewpoints are sometimes called dimensions (such as looking at the same sales by salesperson, or by date, or by customer, or by product, or by region, etc.).
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Databases configured for OLAP use a multidimensional data model, allowing for complex analytical and ad hoc queries with a rapid execution time.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] They borrow aspects of navigational databases, hierarchical databases and relational databases.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is typically contrasted to OLTP (online transaction processing), which is generally characterized by much less complex queries, in a larger volume, to process transactions rather than for the purpose of business intelligence or reporting.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Whereas OLAP systems are mostly optimized for read, OLTP has to process all kinds of queries (read, insert, update and delete).
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] At the core of any OLAP system is an OLAP cube (also called a 'multidimensional cube' or a hypercube).
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] It consists of numeric facts called *measures* that are categorized by *dimensions*.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The measures are placed at the intersections of the hypercube, which is spanned by the dimensions as a vector space.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The usual interface to manipulate an OLAP cube is a matrix interface, like Pivot tables in a spreadsheet program, which performs projection operations along the dimensions, such as aggregation or averaging.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The cube metadata is typically created from a star schema or snowflake schema or fact constellation of tables in a relational database.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Measures are derived from the records in the fact table and dimensions are derived from the dimension tables.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Each *measure* can be thought of as having a set of *labels*, or meta-data associated with it.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] A *dimension* is what describes these *labels*; it provides information about the *measure*.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] A simple example would be a cube that contains a store's sales as a *measure*, and Date/Time as a *dimension*.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Each Sale has a Date/Time *label* that describes more about that sale.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is defined as "a variation of the relational model that uses multidimensional structures to organize data and express the relationships between data".
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The structure is broken into cubes and the cubes are able to store and access data within the confines of each cube.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] "Each cell within a multidimensional structure contains aggregated data related to elements along each of its dimensions".
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Even when data is manipulated it remains easy to access and continues to constitute a compact database format.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is quite popular for analytical databases that use online analytical processing (OLAP) applications.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Analytical databases use these databases because of their ability to deliver answers to complex business queries swiftly.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Data can be viewed from different angles, which gives a broader perspective of a problem unlike other models.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] It has been claimed that for complex queries OLAP cubes can produce an answer in around 0.1% of the time required for the same query on OLTP relational data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The most important mechanism in OLAP which allows it to achieve such performance is the use of *aggregations*.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Aggregations are built from the fact table by changing the granularity on specific dimensions and aggregating up data along these dimensions, using an aggregate function (or *aggregation function*).
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The number of possible aggregations is determined by every possible combination of dimension granularities.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The combination of all possible aggregations and the base data contains the answers to every query which can be answered from the data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Because usually there are many aggregations that can be calculated, often only a predetermined number are fully calculated; the remainder are solved on demand.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The problem of deciding which aggregations (views) to calculate is known as the view selection problem.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] View selection can be constrained by the total size of the selected set of aggregations, the time to update them from changes in the base data, or both.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The objective of view selection is typically to minimize the average time to answer OLAP queries, although some studies also minimize the update time.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Many approaches to the problem have been explored, including greedy algorithms, randomized search, genetic algorithms and A* search algorithm.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Some aggregation functions can be computed for the entire OLAP cube by precomputing values for each cell, and then computing the aggregation for a roll-up of cells by aggregating these aggregates, applying a divide and conquer algorithm to the multidimensional problem to compute them efficiently.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] For example, the overall sum of a roll-up is just the sum of the sub-sums in each cell.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Functions that can be decomposed in this way are called decomposable aggregation functions, and include `COUNT`, `MAX`, `MIN`, and `SUM`, which can be computed for each cell and then directly aggregated; these are known as self-decomposable aggregation functions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In other cases, the aggregate function cannot be computed without analyzing the entire set at once, though in some cases approximations can be computed; examples include `DISTINCT COUNT`, `MEDIAN`, and `MODE`; for example, the median of a set is not the median of medians of subsets.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] These latter are difficult to implement efficiently in OLAP, as they require computing the aggregate function on the base data, either computing them online (slow) or precomputing them for possible rollouts (large space).
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP systems have been traditionally categorized using the following taxonomy.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP (multi-dimensional online analytical processing) is the classic form of OLAP and is sometimes referred to as just OLAP.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP stores this data in an optimized multi-dimensional array storage, rather than in a relational database.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Some MOLAP tools require the pre-computation and storage of derived data, such as consolidations – the operation known as processing.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Such MOLAP tools generally utilize a pre-calculated data set referred to as a data cube.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The data cube contains all the possible answers to a given range of questions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] As a result, they have a very fast response to queries.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] On the other hand, updating can take a long time depending on the degree of pre-computation.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Pre-computation can also lead to what is known as data explosion.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Other MOLAP tools, particularly those that implement the functional database model do not pre-compute derived data but make all calculations on demand other than those that were previously requested and stored in a cache.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Examples of commercial products that use MOLAP are Cognos Powerplay, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy, Microsoft Analysis Services, Essbase, TM1, Jedox, and icCube.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] While ROLAP uses a relational database source, generally the database must be carefully designed for ROLAP use.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] A database which was designed for OLTP will not function well as a ROLAP database.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Therefore, ROLAP still involves creating an additional copy of the data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] However, since it is a database, a variety of technologies can be used to populate the database.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In the OLAP industry ROLAP is usually perceived as being able to scale for large data volumes but suffering from slower query performance as opposed to MOLAP.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP Survey, the largest independent survey across all major OLAP products, being conducted for 6 years (2001 to 2006) have consistently found that companies using ROLAP report slower performance than those using MOLAP even when data volumes were taken into consideration.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] However, as with any survey there are a number of subtle issues that must be taken into account when interpreting the results.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Some companies select ROLAP because they intend to re-use existing relational database tables—these tables will frequently not be optimally designed for OLAP use.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The superior flexibility of ROLAP tools allows this less-than-optimal design to work, but performance suffers.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP tools in contrast would force the data to be re-loaded into an optimal OLAP design.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The undesirable trade-off between additional ETL cost and slow query performance has ensured that most commercial OLAP tools now use a "Hybrid OLAP" (HOLAP) approach, which allows the model designer to decide which portion of the data will be stored in MOLAP and which portion in ROLAP.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] There is no clear agreement across the industry as to what constitutes "Hybrid OLAP", except that a database will divide data between relational and specialized storage.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] For example, for some vendors, a HOLAP database will use relational tables to hold the larger quantities of detailed data and use specialized storage for at least some aspects of the smaller quantities of more-aggregate or less-detailed data.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP addresses the shortcomings of MOLAP and ROLAP by combining the capabilities of both approaches.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP tools can utilize both pre-calculated cubes and relational data sources.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores *aggregations* in MOLAP for fast query performance, and detailed data in ROLAP to optimize time of cube *processing*.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores some slice of data, usually the more recent one (i.e. sliced by Time dimension) in MOLAP for fast query performance, and older data in ROLAP.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Moreover, we can store some dices in MOLAP and others in ROLAP, leveraging the fact that in a large cuboid, there will be dense and sparse subregions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The first product to provide HOLAP storage was Holos, but the technology also became available in other commercial products such as Microsoft Analysis Services, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy and SAP AG BI Accelerator.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The hybrid OLAP approach combines ROLAP and MOLAP technology, benefiting from the greater scalability of ROLAP and the faster computation of MOLAP.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] For example, a HOLAP server may store large volumes of detailed data in a relational database, while aggregations are kept in a separate MOLAP store.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Each type has certain benefits, although there is disagreement about the specifics of the benefits between providers.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Unlike relational databases, which had SQL as the standard query language, and widespread APIs such as ODBC, JDBC and OLEDB, there was no such unification in the OLAP world for a long time.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The first real standard API was OLE DB for OLAP specification from Microsoft which appeared in 1997 and introduced the MDX query language.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Several OLAP vendors – both server and client – adopted it.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In 2001 Microsoft and Hyperion announced the XML for Analysis specification, which was endorsed by most of the OLAP vendors.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Since this also used MDX as a query language, MDX became the de facto standard.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Since September-2011 LINQ can be used to query SSAS OLAP cubes from Microsoft .NET.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The first product that performed OLAP queries was *Express,* which was released in 1970 (and acquired by Oracle in 1995 from Information Resources).
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] However, the term did not appear until 1993 when it was coined by Edgar F.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Codd, who has been described as "the father of the relational database".
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Codd's paper resulted from a short consulting assignment which Codd undertook for former Arbor Software (later Hyperion Solutions, and in 2007 acquired by Oracle), as a sort of marketing coup.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The company had released its own OLAP product, *Essbase*, a year earlier.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] As a result, Codd's "twelve laws of online analytical processing" were explicit in their reference to Essbase.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] There was some ensuing controversy and when Computerworld learned that Codd was paid by Arbor, it retracted the article.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP market experienced strong growth in the late 1990s with dozens of commercial products going into market.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In 1998, Microsoft released its first OLAP Server – Microsoft Analysis Services, which drove wide adoption of OLAP technology and moved it into the mainstream.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP clients include many spreadsheet programs like Excel, web application, SQL, dashboard tools, etc.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Many clients support interactive data exploration where users select dimensions and measures of interest.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Some dimensions are used as filters (for slicing and dicing the data) while others are selected as the axes of a pivot table or pivot chart.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Users can also vary aggregation level (for drilling-down or rolling-up) the displayed view.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Clients can also offer a variety of graphical widgets such as sliders, geographic maps, heat maps and more which can be grouped and coordinated as dashboards.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] An extensive list of clients appears in the visualization column of the comparison of OLAP servers table.
[src:gcp-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Below is a list of top OLAP vendors in 2006, with figures in millions of US Dollars.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:gcp-bigquery/structured-query-language] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
